world_state_legibility (scene-scale, quest-only): The input is a FULL
SCENE. After reading the whole scene, can a new voter reconstruct the
salient world state — active threads, named NPCs present, location,
current goal, any standing threats or promises? Judge on what the scene
actually surfaces, not on background lore it omits.

0.0 = murk. Location unnamed or unclear, NPCs referred to by pronoun or
      unexplained nickname, no active thread legible, no visible goal.
0.3 = one or two facts surface (location OR one NPC named) but threads
      and goals remain implicit.
0.5 = location + characters present are legible, but a voter has to guess
      at which threads are currently active or what the protagonist wants.
0.7 = location, NPCs, active threads, and current goal all surface at
      least once through action or dialogue; a voter can answer "where
      are we and what is at stake" without scrollback.
1.0 = the scene plants every load-bearing state fact in-scene, via action
      and dialogue rather than exposition dump; standing threats and
      promises are re-surfaced at the moment they matter.

Anchors:
  HIGH: a quest update whose opening beat re-establishes the city, names
        the three NPCs at the table, references the outstanding debt in
        dialogue, and closes on the protagonist's stated goal.
  MID : a scene that names the location and one NPC but leaves the reader
        guessing which of three ongoing threads is being advanced.
  LOW : a scene set in an unnamed room between "she" and "him" with no
        recoverable goal or thread.
